{
  "texts": [
    "Commonly, AI is framed in abstract and speculative terms.",
    "In practice, however, AI systems, which underly applications ranging from social media recommendation algorithms to automated weapons, rely on material resources and forms of human labour obtained from different regions of the world (Crawford and Joler 2018).",
    "When taking this infrastructure into account, relevant social and environmental issues come to the fore such as the continuous extraction of human life through data (Couldry and Mejias 2019), the extraction of minerals financing armed conflicts in the Democratic Republic of Congo (Taffel 2015), the exploitative outsourcing of data work in places such as Venezuela (Posada 2022) and e-waste dump areas ranging from Silicon Valley to Africa and Asia (Gabrys 2011).",
    "In recent years, the field of AI ethics has emerged as one of the main platforms for discussion around the risks posed by AI.",
    "Guidelines issued by corporate players, academic institutions and international organisations have tended to emphasise themes such as accountability, privacy and fairness."
  ]
}